privilege which is theirs of performing all the precepts of the Torah, many of which are not 
incumbent upon women.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*29>}29{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}He releases the prisoners of misfortune, passion, sin, hatred and jealousy.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*30>}30{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}To sin unknowingly.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*31>}31{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}To sin willfully.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*32>}32{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}We pray that God will not put us to tests that are too difficult to withstand.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*33>}33{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Should we fail the tests, we will be disgraced.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*34>}34{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}“Favor” means receiving God’s blessings because of our merit.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Si’ach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*35>}35{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}“Kindness” is God’s benevolence bestowed purely by His will, regardless of merit.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Si’ach 
Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*36>}36{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}“Compassion” describes God’s withholding of deserved punishment.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Si’ach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*37>}37{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Genesis{\highlight7 <ITC>} 22:1±19:\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*38>}38{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}These events refer to the previous nine tests by which God tested Abraham. This was to be 
the tenth and the most difficult test of all.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Ha’amek Dovor{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*39>}39{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Isaac was Abraham’s only son by Sarah.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*40>}40{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Ishmael and Eliezer. {\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*41>}41{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Abraham prophesied that both of them would return.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*42>}42{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The Hebrew word is {\highlight7 <IT>}“maacheles”{\highlight7 <ITC>} (root: {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'eb\'ec{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  = to eat) which means that it renders meat fit 
for eating through slaughtering the animal. Another interpretation is: his knife is called 
{\highlight7 <IT>}maacheles{\highlight7 <ITC>} because we still enjoy (eat) the reward of Abraham’s virtue when he agreed to use it 
to slaughter his son.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*43>}43{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Although Isaac understood that he was going to be slaughtered, “They went 
together”Ðwith like hearts.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*44>}44{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The Torah says that he built {\highlight7 <IT>}“the”{\highlight7 <ITC>} altar not just {\highlight7 <IT>}“an”{\highlight7 <ITC>} altar, to indicate that Abraham rebuilt 
the same altar which was originally built by Adam and used by Cain, Abel and by Noah.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Targum 
Yonoson ben Uziel{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*45>}45{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Tradition tells us that this ram was prepared for this purpose from the time of creation. 
{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>} (from {\highlight7 <IT>}Maseches Avos{\highlight7 <ITC>} 5:6)\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*46>}46{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The {\highlight7 <IT>}Midrash{\highlight7 <ITC>} interprets the following: “God will see the binding of Isaac and through its 
merit He will pardon Israel every year and rescue them from trouble. It will thus be said, “On 
this day,” by all generations that the ashes of Isaac are seen by God and serve as our 
atonement.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*47>}47{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}If these blessings were intended to increase the population of Abraham’s descendants, it 
was superfluous, since God had previously blessed him for that purpose. God here blessed the 
descendants of Abraham with the nobility of spirit and courage to fulfill the command to 
sanctify God even when selfsacrifice is required. Only the nation of Israel, Abraham’s children, 
were commanded to fulfill this {\highlight7 <IT>}mitzvoh,{\highlight7 <ITC>} because of the legacy we inherited from him.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Ha’amek 
Dovor.{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*48>}48{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Some people conduct themselves in a Godfearing manner in the presence of others (in 
public), but in the privacy of their homes, do whatever they please. There are others who do just 
the opposite. In private they are governed by fear of God, but in the presence of others they are 
too embarrassed or intimidated to be Godfearing. A Jew must always fear God, in private as well 
as in public.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Si’ach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*49>}49{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Acknowledging the truth is fundamental to serving God, and to all human behavior. One 
who is concerned merely with “winning the argument” will go to any extreme to come out on 
top. This attitude caused the downfall of the 250 leaders who joined Korach, rather than 
acknowledge the truth of Moses’ declaration ({\highlight7 <IT>}Numbers{\highlight7 <ITC>} 16:2±35).Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Si’ach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*50>}50{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}It is not sufficient to merely acknowledge the truth verbally but one must speak truth in 
his heart as well. Rashi on the Talmud ({\highlight7 <IT>}Maseches Makos{\highlight7 <ITC>} 24a) cites the following incident as an 
example of how one should speak truth in his heart: A buyer once offered to purchase an article 
from Rav Safra while he was reciting the {\highlight7 <IT>}Shema.{\highlight7 <ITC>} Because he could not indicate his acceptance, 
the anxious purchaser increased his offer. Rav Safra refused the increment because in his heart 
he had already accepted the original offer.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*51>}51{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Of ourselves or others.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*52>}52{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}In terms of achievement.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Dover Sholom{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*53>}53{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}In terms of time.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Dover Sholom{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*54>}54{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Isaiah{\highlight7 <ITC>} 40:15.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*55>}55{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Others translate, “Children of Abraham who loved You.” See commentaries on {\highlight7 <IT>}Isaiah{\highlight7 <ITC>} 41:8.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*56>}56{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The name Yisrael symbolizes Jacob’s wandering through history proclaiming the 
sovereignty of God, while the name Yeshurun indicates his task to fulfill God’s will as revealed 
to him, and to devote his life to the execution of that which is right in the eyes of God.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}S.R. 
Hirsch{\highlight7 <ITC>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*57>}57{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Deuteronomy{\highlight7 <ITC>} 33:5.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*58>}58{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}For notes, see page 000.\par
